# Comments

Write **self-documenting** code first (clear names, types, structure, small helpers). Add comments **sparingly**, only for **non-obvious _why_** (product rule, version quirk, surprising data shape)—not to restate **_what_** the code does.

Lint/format and `yarn fix-code-style`: **code-style**. Naming: **variable-naming**. This file covers comment **use** only.

Avoid comment text that only points at other files or line numbers—it goes stale. Prefer a short *why* in place. (Examples below stay generic.)

## Default

Omit the comment when control flow and names are enough. Prefer a rename or a small helper over a long explanation.

## When to add a comment

- A **product or UX rule** the code does not make obvious (e.g. show a notice only when there is no hard failure).
- A **surprising input or invariant** so the next reader does not "fix" it incorrectly (e.g. several values in one comma-separated string). Explaining **input shape** next to a cast is *why*, not cast-justification—see **Hygiene**.

## When not to add a comment

Do not narrate each `if` / `else` branch. Prefer clearer names. If one idea is hard (e.g. a feature flag), use **one** short *why* on the **outer** branch instead of a comment on every branch.

**Principle:** comments express **why** (existence, order, edge case)—not **what**.

## Hygiene

When changing **non-generated** files, keep comments accurate—update or remove comments that no longer match behavior.

Do **not** add comments whose main purpose is to justify `as` / `!`. Do **not** leave blocks of commented-out code (use version control). Do **not** add file- or module-level "this file does..." banners. A short *why* next to a cast is fine when it describes real **data shape**, not the cast itself.

Generated/synced paths are out of scope for edits here—see **generated-sdks-and-types**.

## Tests, JSDoc, style

Same comment bar as production code. Do not document that `before` / `beforeEach` is "setup."

Do **not** add JSDoc unless the task explicitly calls for public API documentation.

Prefer `//` for line comments. In JSX, follow ESLint (`{/* ... */}` where required). Keep comments in **English**.

## Issue URLs in comments

Avoid Jira/GitHub URLs in source—track work in the issue tracker; inline links go stale.

## Do not

- Add `TODO`, `FIXME`, or `HACK` markers (reserve those for human authors when appropriate).
- Add `eslint-disable-*` comments—fix the lint issue or leave the code unchanged within the task scope.
- Edit **generated or synced** code or add narrative comments there—follow **generated-sdks-and-types**.

## Snippets (illustrative only)

**Good** — product rule not obvious from JSX alone:

```tsx
<>
  {/* Only show pending notice when nothing is in a hard-failure state */}
  {!failedItems.length && <PendingItemsNotice items={pendingItems} />}
</>
```

**Good** — surprising input shape (*why* for `split`, not cast-justification):

```typescript
function valuesAreAllowed(value: unknown): boolean {
  if (!value) return true;
  // Field can carry multiple values in one comma-separated string
  const entries = (value as string).split(',');
  return entries.every(isAllowedEntry);
}
```

**Avoid** — comments that only narrate branches the code already expresses (noise, easy to drift):

```tsx
const options = React.useMemo(() => {
  if (flag) {
    // When flag is on...
    if (a) {
      // If a, return B
      return B;
    }
    return C;
  }
  return D;
}, [flag, a, B, C, D]);
```
